snippet.textDisplay:
It looks like a computer tower and with tech getting smaller, it is like they are paranoid for another red ring situation. I personally hate the computer tower design. It looks fine if you are on PC, but this is a game console. The design is completely bland and uninspired, and if they need that much space to suck out that much heat, then you are buying a heater. I've never liked Xbox, but I have always tried to give it the benefit of the doubt, but this thing is massive, and it seems like they are trying to make their console seem like it has better stats, while the differences is what you experience don't really seem different. The big bulky design is either because this thing is a heater, or they want it to look like a PC to look "superior". Yes, it is nice to have better stats, but making things better when they are already perceivable the best is just being a try hard. I will still try to test the console, but everything I'm seeing just looks like they are basically clickbaiting with a product.

I didn't really mention the name because at this point I expect Microsoft to give it the least creative and most confusing name possible.

snippet.textDisplay: Looks nice, seems promising, hopeful for big improvements, but.....and this is a big "BUT"...has the disk drive been improved at all in any type of way, and is it any different than the existing Sony 4K Blu-ray Disk drive currently on the X's? I've luckily had no issues with this current gen of Xboxs' besides the disk drive eventually becoming obsolete, or becoming a game in itself of: Insert/Eject. Yes it'll have backwards compatibility, but that doesn't mean much if it's a constant fight to get it to read for example my OG Xbox copy of "Conker: Live & Reloaded". On top of that it's not even playing the game off disc, it's a form of just checking for the rights, that'll allow you to download/access/play the game digitally. This is true and can be proven with "Fallout: New Vegas GOTY Edition" for 360 which has 2-disks, and upon inserting either disc your prompted to download the whole game and all dlc and play, then you can even put the other disc in a second console and do the same. Just showing how it just reads the rights off disc instead of playing it.

snippet.textDisplay: It's funny to me how people who call themselves gamers care about how the graphics look or how many fps the game can run at. Yeah, let's go ahead and put 8k in. Even If our eyes can't perceive it let's do it anyway, who cares. That doesn't sound like something a gamer would say. I've been gaming since 1984. I would play an 8bit game if the game play and story are good before I play a game just because the graphics look good. Beefing up the graphics on a system and making it 8k, something most people are never going to use because I'm pretty sure only very few people own an 8k television if any, isn't going to sell me a system. Yeah the new ssd's and load time decrease are a great addition, but the majority of people just seem to be interested in how good the graphics are. The reason Playstation is my go to is because of the great selection of exclusive titles they have. This doesn't mean I dislike the X-box. I also own a Switch because Nintendo has great games you can only play on their system. If X-box would get some good original games I would buy one. But as of now I can't just so I can play Halo. Beefing up their graphics and frame rates won't sell me their console.

snippet.textDisplay:
Wow... 10 things you didnt need to know and nothing of relevance needed to know.


What is the stance on physical media and offline capability is the primary one.


Also


Clearly the design is intended for vertical usage. That also stems from the primary vent and the whole console being laid out in a smokestack format. Yet the problem that creates is CONSOLES CANT HANDLE READING DISCS FOR SHIT VERTICALLY!!!!!!!! Seriously, this configuration destroys disc drives and has for the last 2 generations since they started pushing it. So how is that going to play out? You lay the thing down to protect the disc drive and you will have overheating as the thing is not optimized to vent heat through that top (unless they change the design) OR you have to run the risk of the disc drive failing within a year.


This seriously smacks of Microsoft being Microsoft and in their "infinite wisdom" trying to Mojave the public yet again and tell us what we need rather than producing what we want. If you can see glaring issues within the first bit of info its a guarantee that this ideology WILL pervade the whole system and its design choices.

snippet.textDisplay:
The GPU in both the PS4 and XBOX One wasn't really the issue. It was the CPU, so it makes sense the GPU is only double the power, while the CPU is 4x what we currently have. That'll help for world generation, texture streaming, and keeping a stable framerate on any kind of game really.

But the proof is in the pudding, as they say, and I will wait until proper reviews are out. If it isn't at least 1080p and 60 FPS constantly, then I'll wait, or just build a desktop PC that will wipe the floor with both the PS5 and XBOX whatever the hell it's called come launch.

I have an NVME M.2 SSD in my laptop as a boot drive, and I would never go back. Windows 10 boots up - with fast start up turned off - in about 15 seconds. If the XBOX has one of those in it, that's a game changer for sure. Those things rock. Would love to get another NVME drive at 1 TB to replace the 5400 drive in my laptop but I'm not so impatient to need my games to load up right now.
